<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-452-641  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 452 641.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE on andamp; about ATandamp;T  Sept 24, 1990 v5 n113 p1(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ATandamp;T Network Systems win: Telefonos de Mexico awards major portionof fiber optic network; will link 54 locations throughout country.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Network Systems (contracts)Telefonos de Mexico S.A. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     ContractsMexicoCommunications Service SuppliersFiber OpticsTransmission LinesLong-Distance Telephone Services.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>ATandamp;T NETWORK SYSTEMS WIN: TELEFONOS DE MEXICO AWARDS MAJOR PORTION  OF FIBEROPTIC NETWORK; WILL LINK 54  LOCATIONS THROUGHOUT COUNTRYandM;Telefonos de Mexico, S.A.andP;  de C.V., Mexico's national telephone company, hasawarded ATandamp;T Network Systems a major portion of a fiber optic network thatwill link 54 locations throughout the country, and significantly enhanceMexico's international long distance infrastructure.andM;ATandamp;T's portion of the contract is valued at $130 million.andM;The total project involves 13,500 kilometers (about 8,000 miles) of fiberoptic cable, and related transmission equipment.andP;  Other vendors will alsoparticipate in the project, which is scheduled to begin this month and becompleted by 1993.andM;ATandamp;T will provide fiber optic cable and related components, and its Spanishsubsidiary, ATandamp;T Network Systems Espana, will provide transmission equipment.andM;ATandamp;T has teamed with Fabricaciones, Ingeniera y Montales, S.A.andP;  (FIMSA), asubsidiary of Grupo ICA, a Mexican engineering and construction firm, toprovide Telmex with a turnkey system for its portion of the fiber opticnetwork.andM;ATandamp;T currently employs almost 4,000 persons in its various facilities inMexico, almost all of them Mexican citizens.andM;ATandamp;T Network Systems is the world's largest manufacturer and marketer ofnetwork telecommunications equipment.andP;  At its cable manufacturing locationsin the U.S., Denmark and the Republic of Korea, ATandamp;T manufacturers enoughfiber cable every nine days to circle the globe.andM;Telmex has been using fiber optic technology for several years.andP;  As a result,when the new network is consolidated with the existing infrastructure, theTelmex network will be one of the most modern in the world with significantbenefits to customers.andP;  Telmex's national network will offer high-qualitytransmission and faster connection speeds for its users, and a larger callhandling capacity.andM;Key Executives: Bill Marx, president, ATandamp;T Network Systems.andO;</TEXT></DOC>